{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"38db7fd4-31f3-431e-acae-f28b971fb5b8","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the breakdown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the default **test ID generation strategy** from `FullyQualified` to `DisplayName`. This produces different test IDs, so Azure DevOps sees every test as brand new.\n\n**Fix** — restore the v3 behavior in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>FullyQualified</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it has no specific test associated with it. Accessing `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`. This is intentional because class init runs once per class, not per test.\n\n**Fix** — remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit` (line 13 in your code), or move that logic into `[TestInitialize]` where a per-test context is available.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`TestContext` setter** | Property should now be `{ get; init; }` — mutable `{ get; set; }` (your line 8) still compiles but is discouraged. |\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit argument conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) no longer happen automatically; match types exactly. |\n| **`[ExpectedException]`** | Deprecated — migrate to `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()` or `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`. |\n| **Parallel execution** | Defaults may differ; review `[Parallelize]` attributes and `.runsettings`. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` (floats)** | Tolerance comparison logic was tightened; edge-case float tests may fail. |\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to apply the fixes to your project files?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f82310e-7c68-473d-b4e2-1781e66302ca","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me address both issues and provide additional guidance based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps** — MSTest v4 changed the default **test ID generation strategy**. In v3, the default was `TestIdGenerationStrategy.FullyQualified` which used the fully qualified name. In v4, the default changed to `TestIdGenerationStrategy.DisplayName`. This changes the test IDs, which causes Azure DevOps (and other test management systems) to see them as entirely new tests, losing history.\n\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` methods is now a \"class-level\" context without test-specific information, so accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException` since class initialization runs once for the entire class rather than per individual test.\n3. Another breaking change to be aware of is that `TestContext` is no longer settable — it should now be defined as a read-only property or use an init accessor instead of allowing full assignment.\n4. Beyond those, there are several other adjustments in MSTest v4: `DataRow` attributes won't automatically convert argument types anymore, `DeploymentItem` behavior has shifted, floating-point assertions now apply proper tolerance checks, parallel execution defaults may differ, and the `ExpectedException` attribute is deprecated in favor of using `Assert.ThrowsException`.","outputTokens":912,"requestId":"7682:14226F:474FA5:53A282:69F2C339"},"id":"812a1333-88ab-44b8-bb6f-938b62aca3e6","timestamp":"2026-04-30T02:49:49.309Z","parentId":"93197028-3af6-4dcb-964b-17ea5ce85e37"}
